"Aronson R.B., Thatje S., Mcclintock J.B., Hughes K.A.","Anthropogenic impacts on marine ecosystems in Antarctica",2011,"Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences","1223","1",,"82","107",,,10.1111/j.1749-6632.2010.05926.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79953156581&partnerID=40&md5=bdb70cf6d0eaafe5aacb8455a1c8c802","Department of Biological Sciences, Florida Institute of Technology, Melbourne, FL, United States; School of Ocean and Earth Science, University of Southampton, National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, United Kingdom; Department of Biology, University of Alabama at Birmingham, Birmingham, AL, United States; British Antarctic Survey, Natural Environment Research Council, Cambridge, United Kingdom","Aronson, R.B., Department of Biological Sciences, Florida Institute of Technology, Melbourne, FL, United States; Thatje, S., School of Ocean and Earth Science, University of Southampton, National Oceanography Centre, Southampton, United Kingdom; Mcclintock, J.B., Department of Biology, University of Alabama at Birmingham, Birmingham, AL, United States; Hughes, K.A., British Antarctic Survey, Natural Environment Research Council, Cambridge, United Kingdom","Antarctica is the most isolated continent on Earth, but it has not escaped the negative impacts of human activity. The unique marine ecosystems of Antarctica and their endemic faunas are affected on local and regional scales by overharvesting, pollution, and the introduction of alien species. Global climate change is also having deleterious impacts: rising sea temperatures and ocean acidification already threaten benthic and pelagic food webs. The Antarctic Treaty System can address local- to regional-scale impacts, but it does not have purview over the global problems that impinge on Antarctica, such as emissions of greenhouse gases. Failure to address human impacts simultaneously at all scales will lead to the degradation of Antarctic marine ecosystems and the homogenization of their composition, structure, and processes with marine ecosystems elsewhere. © 2011 New York Academy of Sciences.","Antarctic Treaty; Antarctica; Biodiversity; Biological invasion; Biotic homogenization; Conservation; Global warming","carbonic acid; chlorphenotane; mineral; polybrominated diphenyl ether; polychlorinated biphenyl; sealant; tributyltin; acidification; Antarctica; anthropology; aquatic fauna; Arctic; benthic fauna; biodiversity; climate change; environmental impact; fishing; food web; global climate; greenhouse effect; greenhouse gas; harvest; human; marine environment; pelagic species; pollution; review; sea surface temperature; shipping; tourism; ultraviolet irradiation; Animals; Antarctic Regions; Aquatic Organisms; Climate; Ecosystem; Environment; Environmental Pollution; Food Chain; Greenhouse Effect; Human Activities; Humans; Oceans and Seas",,"carbonic acid, 3812-32-6, 463-79-6; chlorphenotane, 50-29-3; tributyltin, 688-73-3",,,,"Frenot, Y., Biological invasions in the Antarctic: extent, impacts and implications (2005) Biol. Rev., 80, pp. 45-72; Thomas, D.N., (2008) The Biology of Polar Regions, , Revised Edition. Oxford University Press. Oxford, UK; Tin, T., Impacts of local human activities on the Antarctic environment (2009) Antarct. Sci., 21, pp. 3-33; Frederich, M., Sartoris, F.J., Pörtner, H.-O., Distribution patterns of decapod crustaceans in polar areas: a result of magnesium regulation? (2001) Polar Biol., 24, pp. 719-723; Wittmann, A.C., Held, C., Pörtner, H.O., Sartoris, F.J., Ion regulatory capacity and the biogeography of Crustacea at high southern latitudes (2010) Polar Biol., 33, pp. 919-928; Halpern, B.S., A global map of human impact on marine ecosystems (2008) Science, 319, pp. 948-952; Dayton, P.K., Mordida, B.J., Bacon, F., Polar marine communities (1994) Am. Zool., 34, pp. 90-99; Olbers, D., Borowski, D., Völker, C., Wölff, J.-O., The dynamical balance, transport and circulation of the Antarctic Circumpolar Current (2004) Antarct.